*[[Image:Med 3.png|Bronze]] BRONZE: 4 (1952 1965 1970 1973)

===Intercontinental Cup===
*[[Image:Med 2.png|Silver]] SILVER: 1 (1973)

*[[Image:Med 3.png|Bronze]] BRONZE: 1 (1989)

===Americas Baseball Cup===
*[[Image:Med 1.png|Gold]] GOLD: 1 ([[2008 Americas Baseball Cup|2008]])

===Pan American Games===
*[[Image:Med 2.png|Gold]] SILVER: 2 (1959 1991)

*[[Image:Med 3.png|Bronze]] BRONZE: 4 (1967 1979 1987 1995)

===Caribbean Series===
In 1995, the Senadores de San Juan managed by [[Luis Mel<U+00E9>ndez (baseball)|Luis "Torito" Mel<U+00E9>ndez]], assembled one of the strongest teams in the history of the Caribbean Series.<ref name="Dream Team">{{cite web|url=http://espndeportes.espn.go.com/news/print?id=403752&type=story|title=Dream Teams en la Serie del Caribe|publisher=[[ESPN Deportes]]|language=Sanish|date=2006-01-31|accessdate=2009-02-04}}</ref> The group, which was dubbed "Dream Team", featured Major League Baseball players in most positions, counting with a lineup that included [[Roberto Alomar]], [[Carlos Baerga]], [[Bernie Williams]], [[Juan Gonz<U+00E1>lez (baseball)|Juan Gonz<U+00E1>lez]], [[Edgar Mart<U+00ED>nez]], [[Carlos Delgado]], [[Rub<U+00E9>n Sierra]], [[Rey S<U+00E1>nchez]] and [[Carmelo Mart<U+00ED>nez]].<ref name="Dream Team"/> Puerto Rico's offensive dominated the tournament, eventually winning the Caribbean Series' championship with an undefeated record of 6&ndash;0.<ref name="Dream Team"/> The team was responsible for the only two losses of the Dominican Republic, the country that finished second, scoring victories against [[Pedro Mart<U+00ED>nez]] and [[Jos<U+00E9> Rijo]] in the third and sixth games respectively.<ref name="Dream Team"/>

*14 times Champions: 1951, 1953<U+2013>55, 1972, 1974<U+2013>75, 1978, 1983, 1987, 1992<U+2013>93, 1995, 2000

